{
  "title": "4.1 CONFLICT MANAGEMENT TECHNIQUES",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "b702c97341c30a57",
      "text": "Conflict management techniques have been discussed exhaustively in the various literatures. Pendzich (1994), Anderson, J. Ganthier, M. Thomas, and Wondelleck J. (1996) and Ojiji (2007) identified seven conflict management styles, while Albert (2001) compressed them to four as follows:"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "0f23f835e435d94b",
      "text": "**(i)** Avoidance: This is when the parties to a conflict keep it from the public by not acknowledging it openly. The conflict is denied or ignored and it is characterized by equivocation, changing and avoiding topics, being non-committal, and jovial rather than dealing with the problem at hand (Wilmot and Hocker: 1998:11). It is like the proverbial act of sweeping a problem under the carpet. What happens is that there is a latent conflict which is simmering and can explode unless it is brought into the open and dealt with;"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "3cf66e146e144413",
      "text": "**(ii)** Confrontation: Here, one or more parties to the conflict resort to dealing with the problem unilaterally and even forcefully, or when one party, usually the stronger, tries to impose its will on the other party. This could be through the use of blackmail, intimidation or even military power. The weaker party, in frustration, may resort to unconventional methods to fight back;"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "2a092fd4f09ae08c",
      "text": "**(iii)** Third Party Intervention: This   conflict handling method takes place when a third party (whether solicited or not), intervenes in a conflict. Sometimes, a conflict is taken to a third party acting on behalf of the larger society (e.g. the court of law) which can pronounce mandatorily about who is wrong or right. On the other hand, intervention could be by respected members of the society, acceptable to the conflicting parties;"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "b92a62da1245dbf9",
      "text": "**(iv)** Joint Problem-Solving Strategy: In this technique, parties to the conflicts are made to realize the futility of conflict and agree to negotiate. If they cannot do it by themselves, they can use facilitators who will serve as a moderator between them. This approach results in a win-win situation and it is the best method of conflict management. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "baf66d4b554f441c",
      "text": "The conflicts between farmers and Fulani herdsmen have been managed over time rather than being resolved. As earlier observed, the conflicts basically revolve around competition for a very scarce but vital resource between farmers and herdsmen. The quantum of herds has increased astronomically while grazing land continue to shrink owing to climate change and the resultant desertification. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "f085e5dbfeb75e39",
      "text": "Herdsmen have, therefore, had to migrate southwards to areas which, traditionally, were farming zones in search of lush green vegetation for their animals especially during the dry season. In the course of these movements, conflicts occurred but they were settled through the intervention of Fulani elders and compensation paid appropriately to the farmers. The role of Ruga in managing conflicts in Niger Republic and some parts of Nigeria (earlier discussed)  reiterates the joint intervention. It is clear, therefore, that farmers and Fulanis used the joint-problem method to manage their conflicts in the past. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "d6404e57b69e98f5",
      "text": "Next section **[[4.2 THE ROLE OF GOVERNMENTS IN THE CONFLICT]]**"
    }
